descript.abstract: Classified ShoreZone shoreline segments into 16 shoreline types based on substrate type and elevation. The ShoreZone Inventory characterizes several physical parameters within shoreline segments. The majority of the shoreline is described by line data. Polygon features exist in some areas with extensive shallows. The ShoreZone Inventory includes all saltwater shorelines statewide. It was completed between 1994 and 2000 using aerial videography collected at low tide.
descript.purpose: This line layer shows shoreline type from the larger Washington State ShoreZone Inventory. The ShoreZone Inventory includes all saltwater shorelines statewide based on low-tide aerial video collected 1994-2000.
descript.supplinf: Further information on this dataset is available in The Washington State ShoreZone Inventory User's Manual and The Washington State ShoreZone Inventory Data Dictionary. The data dictionary in particular contains more detailed descriptions of bio-bands. Both of these documents are available online at http://www.dnr.wa.gov

attracc.attraccr: The attributes are based on interpreted videotape, photos and direct observations of a geomorphologist and a marine ecologist all recorded from a helicopter traveling at approximately 60 knots and 300 feet (approx. 90 meters) above the ground. The inventory is a valuable regional data set because it surveyed thousands of miles using consistent methods during a relatively short time frame. However, it cannot replace higher resolution techniques or site-specific surveys. The accuracy of ShoreZone attributes has not been quantified.

qattracc.attracce: No formal accuracy assessment was conducted.

horizpa.horizpar: Spatial data is based on the WA State Dept of Natural Resources digital shoreline (water level line) developed from sources at a scale of 1:24,000.

srcinfo.srccontr: Video imagery of the shoreline was recorded, along with locational information (GPS) during helicopter flights during low tides.
Recorded survey observations of geomorphologist and marine ecologist on the physical and biological features along the shoreline during helicopter flight during low tides.
The WA State Dept of Natural Resources digital shoreline (water level line) provided the base layer for the inventory.
Dept of Natural Resources orthophotos were used in conjunction with survey information and helicopter videography to delineate zones and assign attributes.

procstep.procdesc: Main information source is low-tide, aerial imagery collected during minus tides (below MLLW) in June of the year. Survey data was collected by a marine ecologist, coastal geomorphologist, and a navigator who fly in a helicopter at flight speeds of 60 knots and about 300 feet in altitude. A geomorphologist interpreted the survey data: he defined delineated homogenous units on the DNR orthophotos, and described the units and components in tabular data. A marine ecologist then added tabular data on biological resources. Spatial data is based on the WA State Dept of Natural Resources digital shoreline (water level line).
